        <bioghist>
            <p>Absalom Bull was born in 1797 in Hamptonburgh, Orange County, New York. He was the son of Cadwallader Bull and Submit Watkins, making Absalom the great-grandson of William Bull and Sarah Wells. Absalom married Maria Lindsey (1789-) on September 30, 1822 in Montgomery, N.Y. and they had three children: Hugh (1823-); Maria (1825-1888); and Cadwallader (1827-1863).
In 1821 Absalom and Maria settled in Black Rock. From there Bull held many different positions in Black Rock. He was a lawyer, Erie County Supreme Judge, Secretary of the Black Rock Harbor Company, Justice of Peace, Insurance agent, Tax assessor for Black Rock, Secretary of the Friends of the “American System,” on the Republican Central Committee of Vigilance for Erie County, a NYS Whig for Buffalo, chair for the Buffalo and Black Rock Railroad Company, President of the Board of Trustees for Black Rock, Commissioner of schools in Buffalo, inspector of elections and a collector of tolls for the Erie Canal. Bull passed away on February 21, 1866 of Paralysis.</p>
        </bioghist>
        
        <scopecontent>
            <p>Collection primarily consists of correspondence, legal documents and other papers. The second series chiefly pertains to Peter B. Porter, whom Bull represented.</p>
